-- ⚠️ RE-PINNED 2026-07-14 — THE S2 INVERSION (REJECT -> ACCEPT, prints 4).
-- NOTE the direction: this is the one cell in the arc that went from REJECT to ACCEPT.
-- It is not a weakening.  The old REJECT existed ONLY as a side effect of the method
-- stealing the call: `size 3` dispatched to `Sz.size : Int -> String`, which then
-- clashed with the `: Int` annotation.  Under standalone-wins `size 3` is the user`s
-- own `size : Int -> Int`, so `let s = size 3 : Int` is simply COHERENT and accepts.
-- Everything below describes the OLD rule and is kept for the history only.
--
-- P0-20, the REJECT direction.  Same shadow as p0_20_shadow_literal_user_iface, but the
-- result is pinned to the STANDALONE's return type (`Int`).  Since a literal receiver
-- grounds to `Int` and `impl Sz Int` exists, the occurrence DISPATCHES and yields
-- `String` — so this must be a located `Type mismatch`, on all three engines.
--
-- Before the fix `check` ACCEPTED this (it typed the site against the standalone,
-- `Int -> Int`), so it is the direct check-side regression test: the fix is not "make
-- check silent", it is "make check say what the binary will actually do".
interface Sz a where
  size : a -> String

impl Sz Int where
  size n = "IMPL"

size : Int -> Int
size n = n + 1

main =
  let s = size 3 : Int
  println s
